{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox writer | name = Nigar Rafibeyli | image = Stamps of Azerbaijan, 2013-1088.jpg | caption = House plate on a residence of Rza and Rafibeyli | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1913|06|23}} | birth_place = [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]], Azerbaijan | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1981|07|09|1913|06|23}} | death_place = [[Baku]], Azerbaijan | occupation = Writer | movement = | children = [[Anar Rzayev]] | }}
'''Nigar Khudadat qizi Rafibeyli''' ({{lang-az|Nigar Xudadat qızı Rəfibəyli}}) (1913–1981, [[Baku]]) was an Azerbaijani writer and the Chairman of the Writers' Union of [[Azerbaijan]]. She was the mother of [[Anar Rzayev]], novel and short-story writer, and wife of famous writer and poet [[Rasul Rza]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Reminscences of Uzeyir Hajibeyov | url=http://hajibeyov.com/bio/bio_life/huseinzade_adila/huseinzade_adila.html | accessdate = 17 July 2010 }}</ref>
==Early life== Nigar Rafibeyli was born on 23 June 1913 in the town of [[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]]. Her parents were medical surgeons. Her father, [[Khudadat Rafibeyli]] was the first [[Azerbaijan|Azeri]] surgeon who had studied in Europe. In 1919, he was invited to head the Ganja government by the republican government of [[Azerbaijan Democratic Republic]], but he was soon arrested at instigation by [[Armenians|Armenian]] bolsheviks and sent to [[Nargin (island)|Nargin]] island, where he was executed by bolshevik soldiers.<ref name="ref1">{{Cite web | title = Azerbaycan qadini – Nigar Rafibeyli | url=http://qadin.net/index.php?newsid=438 | accessdate = 17 July 2010 }}</ref> Nigar Rafibeyli finished her school in Ganja and moved to [[Baku]] for her higher education. She studied at Pedagogical Technical School. She taught at school but always wrote novels. Her first poem called "Chadra" (Veil in [[Azerbaijani language|Azeri]]) was published in "Dan Ulduzu" magazine in 1928. In years 1930–1932 she worked in the [[Azerbaijanfilm]] studio. [[File:Rəsul Rza və Nigar Rəfibəylinin Bakıda xatirə lövhəsi.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Plaque on building where Azerbaijani poets [[Rasul Rza]] and Nigar Rafibayli lived in Baku]]
==Later years== In 1931, she worked in [[Azerneshr]] publishing house as the editor and the translator. Rafibeyli then continued her studies in Moscow Pedagogical University. As she studied in Moscow, her first collection of poems was published in Baku. In years 1937–1939, she worked in [[Ushaqneshr]] publishing house. Beginning from 1940, she translated into Azeri many works of famous poets and writers of other nations such as [[Ali-Shir Nava'i|Navai]], [[Schiller]], [[Pushkin]], [[Lermontov]], [[Taras Shevchenko|Shevchenko]] and others. For her great contributions to [[Azerbaijani literature]], she received order of Honour.<ref name="ref1"/> Many of Nigar Rafibeyli's works were dedicated to [[romanticism]], [[motherhood]], [[nature]], [[motherland]].<ref name="ref2">{{Cite web |title = Selected novels of Nigar Rafibeyli |url = http://www.azerikitab.az/site/?category=16&book=802 |accessdate = 17 July 2010 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706130732/http://www.azerikitab.az/site/?category=16&book=802 |archivedate = 6 July 2011 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>
Nigar Rafibeyli died on 9 July 1981. One of streets in Baku bears her name.<ref name="ref1"/>
